---
import Base from '../components/Base.astro';
import { REPO_URL, href } from '../lib/site';
---

<Base title="About" description="What the AI Workshop Tracker is, where the data comes from, and how it's maintained.">
  <section class="masthead">
    <p class="eyebrow">About this site</p>
    <h1>Why this exists</h1>
  </section>

  <div class="prose">
    <p>
      AI and robotics conferences each host dozens of workshops a year, and every one has its own website, its own
      (often extended) deadline, and its own way of publishing accepted papers. Two things have
      never had a home. Conference deadline trackers exist, but <em>workshop</em> deadlines have
      never had one. The accepted papers are just as scattered, spread across hundreds of separate
      workshop pages and proceedings sites, with no way to search across all of them at once. This
      site is that missing board, where every workshop deadline and every workshop paper become
      searchable in one place.
    </p>
    <h2>Where the data comes from</h2>
    <p>
      Every workshop is a small YAML file in a <a href={REPO_URL}>public GitHub repository</a>,
      maintained by the community — organizers and submitters add and fix entries via pull
      requests or a simple form. Submission deadlines and accepted-paper lists are fetched automatically from the
      <a href="https://openreview.net" rel="noopener">OpenReview</a> API for workshops hosted there
      (deadlines come from the venue record or its submission invitation); other workshops link to
      their own proceedings pages, and missing deadlines are filled in by contributors.
    </p>
    <h2>Accuracy</h2>
    <p>
      Deadlines get extended, pages move, and some entries are unverified estimates (marked as
      such). <strong>Always confirm details on the official workshop website before planning a
      submission.</strong> Found something wrong? Every page has an “Edit” link — fixes typically
      take a one-line change.
    </p>
    <h2>Licensing &amp; reuse</h2>
    <p>
      The workshop data and paper caches are <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/" rel="noopener">CC-BY-4.0</a>;
      the site code is MIT. A machine-readable dump of everything is at
      <a href={href('/api/workshops.json')}><code>/api/workshops.json</code></a>, and new entries are
      announced in an <a href={href('/rss.xml')}>RSS feed</a>.
    </p>
    <h2>Add or fix a workshop</h2>
    <p>
      <a class="btn" href={`${REPO_URL}/issues/new?template=add-workshop.yml`}>Open the 2-minute form</a>
    </p>
    <p>
      Fill in what you know and a bot turns it into a validated pull request — no Git needed.
      Prefer editing directly? Every workshop page has a <strong>✎ Edit</strong> link to its data
      file, and <a href={`${REPO_URL}/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md`}>CONTRIBUTING.md</a> documents the
      format. Data you submit is published under CC-BY-4.0.
    </p>
    <h2>Saving workshops &amp; papers</h2>
    <p>
      Star <span class="star-demo">☆</span> any workshop or paper, whether on the deadline board,
      in search results, or on a workshop page, and it appears on
      <a href={href('/saved/')}>your saved list</a>. Saved items are stored only in your browser
      (localStorage). There's no account, no cookies, and nothing sent to a server, which also means
      the list doesn't follow you across devices and is erased if you clear this site's data.
    </p>
    <h2>Calendar feeds</h2>
    <p>
      Subscribable <code>.ics</code> deadline feeds exist but are paused while imported dates are
      being verified — a wrong deadline in your calendar is worse than none. They'll return once
      the data is vetted.
    </p>
    {/* "Support this project" — hidden for launch. Remove this comment wrapper to restore.
    <h2>Support this project</h2>
    <p>
      The tracker is free, open source, and ad-free, and the data is openly licensed —
      see the <a href="https://github.com/Yeping-Hu/ai-workshop-tracker/blob/main/CONTRIBUTOR_TERMS.md">contributor terms</a>.
      If it saved you during deadline week, you can
      <a href="https://github.com/sponsors/Yeping-Hu">sponsor its maintenance</a>; donations
      go toward the domain and keeping the data fresh.
    </p>
    */}
  </div>
</Base>
